output_contract.section:
What everyone thinks is happening; what is actually happening; why the truth is hidden; who knows
the truth; who suspects part of it; who benefits from the lie; who would be destroyed by the truth;
what evidence exists; why the truth matters now; how the truth changes the meaning of the opening premise.

Boxed text; immediate sensory immersion; the first NPC interaction; a visible problem; a hidden clue;
a reason to act now; a moment of player choice; three possible first actions; GM guidance for each
first action; how to move into the broader adventure.

What players can discover by: wandering; asking questions; studying the environment; breaking rules;
helping ordinary people; following money, food, water, labor, or logistics; watching rituals; noticing
what is missing. Then add at least: 12 ambient discoveries; 8 rumors; 6 omens; 6 strange local customs;
6 signs the hidden truth is leaking into daily life.

Social norms players should understand; etiquette mistakes and consequences; who will talk freely;
who requires leverage; who lies automatically; who tells the truth for the wrong reason; what bribes
work; what threats backfire; what public reputation does; how factions respond to player behavior;
how ordinary people interpret the players. Include a social consequence table with columns:
Player behavior | Immediate reaction | Later consequence | Faction affected.

Content warnings; lines and veils suggestions; tone dials; horror dials; violence dials; humor dials;
romance dials if relevant; player consent check-in prompts; how to fade to black; how to replace
disturbing content while preserving stakes.

Premise in 3 sentences; hidden truth in 3 sentences; main NPCs; main factions; key locations;
essential clues; escalation clock summary; session timeline; encounter list; finale triggers;
ending menu; emergency improvisation rules.
